    head
      meta(charset='utf-8')
      meta(name='viewport' content='width=device-width, initial-scale=1')
      meta(name='referer' content='always')
      link(rel='stylesheet' href='../styles.css')
      title Ali's Portfolio - Spellbook
    body
        header#home(name='home')
          .container
            nav.flex.items-centre.justify-between
              .left.flex.justify-right
                .logo
                  img(src='../img/Spellbook/spellbook_logo.JPG' alt='Spellbook logo')
                div
                  a(href='../index.html') Back
              .right
                a(href='#contacts')
                  button.btn.btn-primary Contact
            .hero.flex.items-centre.justify-between
              .left.flex-1.justify-center
                img(src='../img/Spellbook/spellbook_funnyman.jpg' alt='Spellbook landing page')
              .right.flex-1
                h6
                  i Spellbook
                iframe(frameborder="0" src="https://itch.io/embed/1967752?linkback=true")
                  a(href="https://kingben.itch.io/spellbook" target="_blank")
                    p Spellbook by KingBen, zzzergling, codypfrunder, davidlh123, dnajerab, RydalisDarx, Poorgrammer, Niikonnen, k10c
                p(style='padding-top:1rem')
                  i Spellbook is a bullet-hell boss-rush game in which you cast spells and dodge attacks all using your keyboard. 
                    | Both of these mechanics revolve around pressing certain keys or typing certain words. 
                    | Test your typing speed and reflexes in this fast-paced, action-heavy take on a typing game.
                p(style='padding-top:1rem')
                  | Games can be both fun and help train people's skills, in this case, we aimed to help people get use to typing.
                  | Many people dont know how to type properly or type without looking at their hands. I joined the Spellbook team as a 
                  | programmer to make the basis of the typing system used to cast spells, allowing people to input a spell command while 
                  | dodging attacks enemies throw at them, alongside information screens. This is the first formal project I joined, 
                  | so indulge me in my learning process.
        section#info.info(name='info')
          .container.flex.items-centre
            .left.flex-1.justify-center
              img.content-medium.imgfloat-left(src='../img/Spellbook/spellbook_prototype.JPG' alt='The main gameplay with no art implemented')
            .right.flex-1
              h1.left-margin
                | Learning  
                span Unity
              p.left-margin
                | I walked into the team with a decently strong grasp of C++ and Java, getting my A.S. in Computer Science before transfering to UC Irvine 
                | and joining the Spellbook team as my first game. Because of my prior experience, I knew learning C# would be easy, but learning the structure
                | of Unity and the game development pipeline was going be harder. Spellbook's team of people were much more experienced with game development than 
                | I was, so I played a more supplementary role doing the smaller things, or so I hoped I would.
              p.left-margin
                | The first thing I worked on was one of the core parts of the gameplay loop: the spell input system. Since this was the beginning of development, I 
                | also needed to make some spells to test the system as well, so I needed to learn a lot about Unity very quickly. I read almost an entirely book worth of 
                | Unity documentation, in which I learned about Scriptable Objects and Colliders, and made myself a small fireball effect to test on enemies.
              p.left-margin
                | Of course, I needed the system to be expandable for multiple spells and telling the game when someone is typing a spell, or typing to move.
        section#info.info(name='info')
          .container.flex.items-centre
            .left.flex-1.justify-center
              img.content-small.imgfloat-left(src='../img/Spellbook/spellbook_gameplay.JPG' alt='The main character casting FIRE')
            .right.flex-1
              h1.left-margin
                | Applying and Expanding my  
                span Learnings
              p.left-margin
                | To seperate movement and casting, I made it so all capital letter inputs would cast spells. This meant that lowercase letters would move the player 
                | and uppercase letters would add to the casting string. Afterwards, a simple Enter button press would fire the spell off if you spelled it correctly.
                | We did not have to account for inputs simultaneously moving and casting, since we seperated it by character input and not button input, vastly simplifying 
                | the input system and not relying on two seperate input controllers for movement and casting. This would be beneficial in other ways too, since through QA
                | testing we found that people did not want to hold down the Shift key to cast spells and wanted to have a toggle, which already existed in this implementation 
                | in the form of the CapsLock key! 
              p.left-margin
                | Alongside my fireball, I made a rudementary spell factory that will create a new spell at runtime based on this input system I made, which would only be 
                | the fireball when inputting "FIRE". However, as new spells were made, adding it to the system became simple as all the new spell effect needed to do was implement 
                | the SpellFactory and have stats based on the Scriptable Object created for the spell. In retrospect, this system could be refined and a layer of abstraction can be
                | removed, but this system was already expandable and adaptable out the gate. 
        section#info.info(name='info')
          .container.flex.items-centre
            .left.flex-1
              h1
                | Working on  
                span UX Engineering
              p.right-margin
                | After implementing the basis of the spell system, I realized there were a lot of parts to the game that felt unintitive to users learning to type. So, 
                | I started developing parts of the user experience, like the tutorial, spellcasting interface, and information screens. I stopped programming as much and
                | instead worked with Unity's internal systems of Canvases and TextMeshes to make portions of the spellcasting interface, which shows the string you are constructing 
                | when you are casting spells.  
              p.right-margin
                | Alongside that, I worked on portions of the level select screen and the spell description page. These are to make sure players know what each spell in the game does 
                | and can find a boss to fight without having to replay the tutorial of the game. Though, this also allows players to replay the tutorial whenever they want, if they take 
                | a break from playing or need a refresher of how some things work. I wanted the game to play well, but I also wanted people to know how to play it.
            .right.flex-1.justify-center
              img.content-medium.imgfloat-right(src='../img/Spellbook/spellbook_levelselect.JPG' alt='The boss select of Spellbook')
        section#info.info(name='info')
          .container.flex.items-centre
            .left.flex-1
              h1
                | The Final 
                span Build
              p.right-margin
                | At the end of production, I realized what I wanted to focus on in my game development carrer. I loved 2D games and thinking about the user experience, but I also 
                | enjoyed making well constructed back-end systems that store and send information between the user and system. This would be the start of what I would come to love in the 
                | game development life cycle.
              p.right-margin
                | You can watch some gameplay on the right, play the game on 
                a(href="https://kingben.itch.io/spellbook" target="_blank") itch.io
                |  and even see exactly what work I did on the game by looking at the 
                a(href="https://github.com/BenWargowski/Spellbook/commits/main/?author=RydalisDarx" target="_blank") commit history
                |  on the game's maintained GitHub repository.
            .right.flex-1.justify-center
